{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7b63a45b-7d0e-4bc2-ab8f-2ed9ceec4c02","content":"Neither — use **`dotnet watch`**.\n\n- `dotnet watch` monitors your source files and automatically rebuilds/reruns when changes are detected. That's the hot reload experience.\n- `dotnet run` does a single build-and-run with no file watching.\n- `dotnet test` runs tests once and exits.\n\nFor a test project like yours, use:\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch test\n```\n\nThis will re-run your tests automatically whenever you save a file change.\n\n> **Tip:** Setting `DOTNET_WATCH_RESTART_ON_RUDE_EDIT=true` ensures the app restarts even for changes that can't be applied in-place.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"009d117a-ae4c-40dc-81b5-4774b35c46e3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET hot reload - specifically whether to use `dotnet test` or `dotnet run` to benefit from hot reload. Let me look at the project files to understand the context.","outputTokens":217,"requestId":"E3C7:314AF9:6F7685:7FD7D7:6A0529EE"},"id":"9604f940-95c2-4b47-ba41-ddfec77f465a","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:48:38.010Z","parentId":"bb23be26-5f12-4d1d-a636-ecc1e5fcde50"}
